The grammar generates strings starting from A, which expands to BC. B produces one or more x's, and C can become B (more x's) or D, which produces y possibly preceded by z from E.  
Option C, "xz", cannot be generated because C must produce at least one y (via D) or more x's (via B), and there is no path to produce just "xz".  

